Title: Syntax Adjustments
------------------------------------

# Syntax adjustments

Plain Markdown gives you emphasis, links, lists, headings, and code, and very
little else. For day-to-day prose that is enough; for the kind of writing this
manual is built for — technical, typographic, dual-targeted at the web *and*
print — it leaves several common needs unspoken. How do you mark a passage as
*intense* without leaning on raw HTML? How do you typeset a chemical formula or
an exponent? How do you flush a stanza to the right margin, or attach a CSS class
to a list item, without abandoning Markdown altogether?

JMarkdown answers with a small set of **syntax adjustments**: a handful of inline
shorthands, two block alignment forms, emoji and icon insertion, and a way to
pin classes and an `id` onto an element. None of them require dropping into HTML,
and — crucially — the typographic ones produce both HTML *and* LaTeX from the
same source, so a document written once typesets correctly for screen and for
the printed page.

This page is a tour of those adjustments, from the inline emphasis shorthands
through alignment, icons, and class attachment. Throughout, the live demos show
the source on the left and its rendered result on the right, so nothing here can
drift from what JMarkdown actually does.

> **One inline syntax replaces Markdown's, by design.** The emphasis shorthands
> below — `/italics/`, `*strong*`, and the rest — are JMarkdown's *own* inline
> grammar, registered in place of (not alongside) the CommonMark spellings. This
> is deliberate: a single, unambiguous set of markers. If you would rather author
> in standard Markdown emphasis (`_italics_`, `**bold**`), pass the `-n`
> (`--normal-syntax`) flag to `jmarkdown process`, which suppresses the whole
> family in this section and reverts to stock behaviour. Everything else on this
> page (alignment, emoji, classes) is always available.

## Inline emphasis

JMarkdown provides six inline emphasis markers. Each wraps a short run of text,
each nests inside the others, and each renders to the natural HTML element for
the screen and the natural command for LaTeX.

:::markdown-demo
Writing /italics/ gives italics.

Writing *strong* gives strong (bold).

Writing __underline__ gives an underline.

Writing ==highlight== marks text as highlighted.

Writing **intense** gives bold-italic emphasis.
:::

### The six markers

| You write | Web (HTML) | Print (LaTeX) | Meaning |
|---|---|---|---|
| `/text/` | `<em>` | `\emph{…}` | italics / emphasis |
| `*text*` | `<strong>` | `\textbf{…}` | strong (bold) |
| `__text__` | `span.underline` | `\underline{…}` | underline |
| `==text==` | `span.highlight` | `\hl{…}` | highlight |
| `**text**` | `span.intense` | `\textbf{\emph{…}}` | intense (bold-italic) |

A few points worth knowing:

- **The web and print forms are not the same element.** `==highlight==` and
  `**intense**` render as a styled `<span>` on the web, so you control their
  appearance entirely through CSS (the docs stylesheet, for instance, gives
  `span.highlight` a coloured background and `span.intense` a heavier weight).
  In LaTeX they map to commands: `==…==` becomes `\hl{…}`, which is provided by
  the **`soul`** package — add `\usepackage{soul}` (or `\usepackage{xcolor}` +
  `soul`) to your preamble if you use highlighting in print.
- **`**…**` is *intense*, not Markdown's bold.** In stock Markdown a double
  asterisk means bold; in JMarkdown it means bold-italic (the "intense" style),
  and a *single* asterisk is the one that means bold. This is the most common
  surprise for authors arriving from CommonMark, so it is worth fixing in
  memory: one star is strong, two stars are intense.

### Nesting

The emphasis markers nest, which lets you combine effects. The reliable way to
combine two is to bracket the inner pair *inside* the outer pair — closing the
markers in the reverse of the order you opened them, exactly as you would nest
parentheses:

:::markdown-demo
Bold inside italic: /*italic bold*/.

Italic inside bold: */bold italic/*.

Underline can wrap mixed emphasis:
__underline with *bold* and /italic/ inside__.
:::

That is, `/*…*/` reads as "open italic, open bold, close bold, close italic" and
produces correctly nested `<em><strong>…</strong></em>`; `*/…/*` does the same
the other way round. Properly nested markers always behave; *crossed* markers
(opening italic then bold but closing italic first, as in `/*…/*`) do **not**
form a clean nest and will produce ragged output, so keep your pairs balanced.

### How the italics marker reads its content

The slash marker is intentionally conservative about what it will treat as
italics, so that ordinary slashes in prose — dates, paths, and/or fractions —
are not swept up by accident. A run of `/…/` becomes italics only when the text
between the slashes contains **no internal slash** and **no sentence-ending
punctuation** (`.`, `?`, `!`) except, optionally, a single such mark at the very
end:

:::markdown-demo
Multi-word italics work: /two whole words/.

A trailing full stop is allowed: /like this./

But a slash in a path is left alone: see /usr/local/bin for the binary.
:::

This is why `and/or` and `/usr/local` survive untouched: each contains an
interior slash, so the tokenizer declines to treat it as emphasis. When you want
italics around a phrase that itself contains a slash or a mid-sentence full stop,
reach for the explicit container form (`:span[…]{}`) described in
[Directives](directives-syntax.html), or fall back to `\emph` / `<em>` directly.

### Subscripts and superscripts

Two more inline markers handle the most common scientific typesetting needs
without invoking the math engine. An underscore introduces a subscript; a caret
introduces a superscript. By default each consumes a single following character;
to subscript or superscript a longer run, wrap it in braces:

:::markdown-demo
Water is H_2O and the famous identity is E=mc^2.

For longer runs, brace them: H_{2}O and x^{2n+1}.
:::

On the web these become `<sub>` and `<sup>`; in LaTeX they become
`\textsubscript{…}` and `\textsuperscript{…}`. Note that these are *text-mode*
sub/superscripts for use in running prose. For mathematical sub/superscripts
inside an expression, write the expression as math — see
[Math Support](math-support.html) — where `_` and `^` carry their usual TeX
meaning.

## Aligned blocks

Two block-level forms set a span of text flush right or centred, without any
per-line break markup. Both are line-oriented: each source line becomes its own
line in the output, so they suit addresses, verse, attributions, and short
display passages where Markdown's "lines flow into one paragraph" behaviour is
exactly what you do *not* want.

### Flush right

Prefix each line with `>>` to push the block to the right margin. Line breaks
within the block are preserved (you do not need trailing-space breaks, which
JMarkdown disables anyway — see [Disabled Syntax](disabled-syntax.html)), and
blank lines start new paragraphs as usual:

:::markdown-demo
>> This text is right aligned.
>> Multiple lines can be included as
>> line breaks are not assumed
>> to be significant.
>>
>> And multiple paragraphs can be included
>> as well!
:::

### Centred

To centre instead, mark *both ends* of every line: open with `>>` and close with
`<<`. The trailing `<<` is what distinguishes a centred block from a flush-right
one, so the closing markers need not line up in any particular column — pad them
to wherever is convenient in your source:

:::markdown-demo
>> This text is center aligned.      <<
>> Multiple lines can be included as <<
>> line breaks are not assumed       <<
>> to be significant.                <<
>>                                   <<
>> Multiple paragraphs are           <<
>> supported, too!                   <<
:::

Both forms emit a wrapping `<div>` — `div.jmarkdown-right` and
`div.jmarkdown-center` respectively — and the body of that `<div>` is parsed as
full Markdown, so emphasis, links, and the other inline shorthands all work
inside an aligned block. The alignment itself is supplied by CSS on those two
classes (the docs stylesheet sets `text-align` accordingly).

## Emoji and icons

JMarkdown recognises a colon-delimited shorthand for two icon families: GitHub's
"octocat" emoji set, and Font Awesome icons.

### GitHub emoji

Put an emoji's short name between colons. The name is replaced by an inline image
of the corresponding emoji:

:::markdown-demo
I :heart: writing in JMarkdown.
:::

The full set of recognised names is large; consult the
[list of octocat emoji](https://gist.github.com/rxaviers/7360908) for the
complete catalogue.

### Font Awesome icons

The same `:name:` syntax doubles as a Font Awesome shorthand, *provided the name
begins with `fa-` immediately after the opening colon*. A bare `:fa-thumbs-up:`
renders the thumbs-up icon:

:::markdown-demo
A job well done: :fa-thumbs-up:
:::

You can append extra Font Awesome modifier classes after the icon name, separated
by spaces. You do **not** repeat the `fa-` prefix on the modifiers — JMarkdown
adds it for you — so `:fa-thumbs-up lg rotate-90:` is shorthand for the classes
`fa-thumbs-up fa-lg fa-rotate-90`:

:::markdown-demo
Sized and rotated: :fa-thumbs-up lg rotate-90:
:::

Two practical requirements:

- **The `fa-` must come first.** The `fa-` prefix has to follow the opening colon
  *immediately* (`:fa-thumbs-up:`, never `:thumbs-up fa-...:`); that prefix is how
  JMarkdown tells a Font Awesome request apart from an octocat name.
- **Load the Font Awesome stylesheet/script.** Font Awesome icons are rendered as
  an `<i class="fa-solid …">` element, which only displays once the Font Awesome
  package is linked in your document's `<head>`. JMarkdown emits the markup but
  does not bundle the library; add the appropriate Font Awesome link (commonly via
  the [Add to head](output-templates.html) metadata, or your output template) so
  the glyphs appear. Octocat emoji, by contrast, are plain images and need no
  external library.

> **A note on LaTeX output.** The emoji and icon shorthands target the web. In
> LaTeX mode they currently emit their HTML markup unchanged rather than a print
> equivalent, so avoid them in passages destined for print, or guard the icon in a
> web-only block. The emphasis, sub/superscript, and alignment forms above *do*
> translate to LaTeX, as the tables note.

## Classes and an id on any element

Standard Markdown gives you no way to attach a CSS class or an `id` to the element
it generates. JMarkdown borrows the directive system's attribute syntax for this:
write a brace block beginning with `.` (a class) or `#` (an id) at the end of the
text, and the class(es) and id are attached to the **enclosing element** — the
list item, paragraph, heading, or whatever Markdown produced from that text.

Assuming `.red` and `.lightgreen` are classes you have defined in CSS, you can tag
individual list items:

:::markdown-demo
1. This is a list item {.red}
2. This is another item {.lightgreen #foo}
3. This is yet another.
:::

The same brace block works on a paragraph — placing it at the end of the
paragraph's text attaches the class to the `<p>`:

:::markdown-demo
This whole paragraph carries a class. {.lightgreen}
:::

You can list several classes and an id together; classes start with `.`, the id
with `#`, separated by spaces, as in `{.red .lightgreen #foo}`. The brace block
is consumed — it never appears in the output — and the attributes are hoisted onto
the parent element after rendering.

How it works under the hood is worth a sentence, because it explains the one
limitation. JMarkdown cannot rewrite an element that has not been generated yet,
so the marker first emits an invisible placeholder span carrying the requested
classes and id as data attributes; a post-processing pass then walks the rendered
HTML, copies those attributes onto the placeholder's parent element, and deletes
the placeholder. The practical consequence: the brace block attaches to whatever
element *directly contains* it, so place it inside the text of the element you mean
to tag.

In **LaTeX** mode the class/id marker emits nothing at all — there is no general
mapping from a CSS class to a LaTeX construct. When you need print-specific
formatting at the same spot, supply it explicitly with the `:TeX[…]` inline
directive (see [Directives](directives-syntax.html)). For richer structural
attributes — turning a region into a `section` or `aside`, setting arbitrary
`key=value` attributes — the full [Directives](directives-syntax.html) grammar is
the better tool; the `{.class #id}` shorthand is the lightweight option for the
common case of "just put a class on this".

## Reference

### Inline markers

| Marker | Example | Web | LaTeX |
|---|---|---|---|
| Italics | `/text/` | `<em>` | `\emph{…}` |
| Strong | `*text*` | `<strong>` | `\textbf{…}` |
| Underline | `__text__` | `span.underline` | `\underline{…}` |
| Highlight | `==text==` | `span.highlight` | `\hl{…}` (needs `soul`) |
| Intense | `**text**` | `span.intense` | `\textbf{\emph{…}}` |
| Subscript | `_x` or `_{xyz}` | `<sub>` | `\textsubscript{…}` |
| Superscript | `^x` or `^{xyz}` | `<sup>` | `\textsuperscript{…}` |

### Block and inline forms

| Form | Syntax | Produces |
|---|---|---|
| Flush right | each line prefixed `>>` | `div.jmarkdown-right` |
| Centred | each line `>>` … `<<` | `div.jmarkdown-center` |
| GitHub emoji | `:name:` | inline emoji image |
| Font Awesome | `:fa-name modifiers:` | `<i class="fa-solid fa-name …">` |
| Class / id | `{.class #id}` at end of text | classes + id on the parent element |

### The `-n` / `--normal-syntax` flag

| Flag | Effect |
|---|---|
| `-n`, `--normal-syntax` | Disable JMarkdown's inline emphasis family (italics, strong, underline, highlight, intense, sub/superscript) and revert to standard Markdown emphasis (`_em_`, `**bold**`). Alignment, emoji, icons, and class/id are unaffected. |

